Brand New Muzzle Brake/Quick Mount for M1A. Below is manufacture description:

 The Gemtech 7.62mm QUICKMOUNT is a precision machined, heat treated suppressor adapter. It is available in a number of thread patterns to fit most popular 7.62mm rifles currently on the market. 

 There are three main types of QUICKMOUNTS available: Tensioning, VORTEX, and Standard "Phantom" style mounts. 

 The Tensioning style, which is generally for longer bolt action rifles not requiring a true flash hider. It is threaded from the front, telescoping back over the barrel, which must be specially profiled to fit this mount. This makes a shorter overall profile, moving the suppressor back further, and also tensions the last inches of barrel for accuracy. It has no flash hider slots, as this portion of the mount is behind the crown. 

 The VORTEX is for the ultimate in flash reduction and accuracy: GEMTECH and Smith Enterprises have joined forces to offer a QUICKMOUNT version of the proven Vortex tm flash hider (5/8-24 only). This gives the best flash reduction available when using your rifle with or without the suppressor mounted. 

 The Standard 7.62mm QUICKMOUNT fits our HVT, QUICKSAND and older TPR-S suppressors. It features a more conventional flash hider design, and is available in the most thread pitches for a wide variety of host weapons, such as: 5/8-24 (DPMS, Armalite, etc.), M18x1mm (Sako TRG or Tikka, Blaser LRS), M18x1.5 (Accuracy International), M14x1mm LH (AK-47), 9/16-24 LH ( FN FAL), and 1/2-28 (does not fit 5.56mm suppressors, some 6.8SPC and 6.5 rifles use this pitch, and it may be used to fit an HVT or QUICKSAND for subcaliber usage on 5.56mm weapons), M15x1mm (HK 91),and M13x1mm RH ( Galil). 

 For M1A rifles (except SOCOM 16") you can utilize a 5/8-24 threaded flash hider mount (Phantom or Vortex) with our M1A Adapter. 

 As a safety feature, our 5.56mm suppressors will *not* fit onto our 7.62mm adapters.

LWRC M6A2 Short Stroke Gas Piston 5.56 NATO AR15 Carbine with a Nikon M-223 4-16x40 Sniper Scope.

The M6 is designed and manufactured by Land Warfare Resources Corporation.

It is based on the M4 carbine, with which it shares 80% of its parts.

It features a proprietary short-stroke self-regulating gas piston system and bolt carrier/carrier key design, which prevents trapped gases from contacting the bolt carrier or receiver of the weapon, which reduces the heating and carbon fouling of the internals, simplifies field maintenance, and improves reliability.

All M6A2 Rifles Feature a Match Grade, cold rotary hammer forged barrel with a target crown.

The barrel is treated with NiCorr™ surface conversion technology that extends service life, enhances accuracy, and increases the effective range of the weapon.

The bolt carrier group and the barrel extension of the M6A2 rifle is coated with EXO’s patented nickel-boron surface conversion technology that provides a hard permanent lubrication to the moving parts.

This M6A2 has a low- profile gas block and there is no A-frame front sight to obscure the field of view of the optical device.

It also features a longer mid-length free float rail system with rail covers and a removable return-to-zero top so that any M4 MIL Std 1913 accessory can be mounted to the rail.

The rail has a monolithic profile so you can bridge devices from the receiver to the rail seamlessly and the longer rail also affords more 1913 “real estate” to mount your accessories.

This High-End Rig is Topped with a High-End Nikon M-223 4-16x40 Sniper Scope with BDC.

It also has MOE Magpul Stock and a Magpul MIAD Pistol Grip.

postcontent:
Smith & Wesson 460 ES .460XVR S&W Magnum Emergency Bear Survival Kit (Limited production) Hard to find, and sell fast. 

Pistol has fired 50 rounds. Please email me for more pictures.

•	Model: 460XVR 

•	Caliber: .460 

•	Barrel Length: 2 3/4" 

•	Front Sight: Red Ramp 

•	Rear Sight: Adjustable 

•	Grip: Rubber 

•	Frame: Extra Large 

•	Finish: Satin Stainless 

•	Overall Length: 9" 

•	Material: Stainless Steel 

•	Weight Empty: 54.8 oz. 

The 460 Magnum chambering in a revolver is special because of its versatility. It can shoot anything from 45 Colt loads, to 45 Colt +P, 45 Long Colt, 454 Casull and 460 Magnum cartridges in bullet weights ranging from 200 to 400 grains. In a first for a production revolver, the S&W 460 series of revolvers were designed from their conception to also shoot spire-point bullets.



S&W Model 460ES - Emergency Survival Tool Kit contains: 

•	Smith & Wesson Model 460XVR 

•	2 3/4" Barrel with Bright Yellow Hogue recoil reducing grip 

•	Waterproof Storm Case 

•	Blast Match 

•	Fire starter and Wet-Fire tender 

•	Saber Cut 

•	Saw with fabric sheath 

•	Jet Scream whistle 

•	Star Flash signal mirror 

•	Polaris compass 

•	Two MPI Mylar Space Emergency Blankets 

•	Smith & Wesson Extreme Ops Liner Lock Folding Knife with Black Sheath 

•	"Bear Attacks of the Century - True Stories of Courage and Survival" book by Larry Mueller and Marguerite Reiss 





The gun itself is a premium firearm. It is finished in satin stainless with a bead-blasted finish on the top of the receiver to reduce glare. It features a red-notch front sight and a target adjustable rear sight. 

The chambers are polished to a mirror-like shine for ease of extraction which I have found to be more of a necessity than a luxury when dealing with cartridges that operate at 60,000 P.S.I. The forcing cone has been polished to reduce gas-cutting of the cone and receiver. The muzzle has a recessed crown. 

The action is very slick and it has the typical “Smooth and Wesson” trigger that at an estimate breaks at a little over 3 lbs. in single action. 

Its proportions look right and it balances very well in the hand being slightly muzzle heavy but not overly so. The grips are an excellent shape and do their job of absorbing recoil well. 

Also included are a brand new Galco holster and black Pachmayr Decelerator grips.

title: For Sale:  FN Special Police Rifle SPR Custom 24" 308 competition ready
location: Colorado Springs area, Colorado Springs, Colorado
postcontent:
I don't want to sell, but need too after our house was hit by lightning.

This it a strange rifle from the beginning.  I bought it in pieces, then built it from there.  I bought the FN SPR action and bottom metal together from a dealer.  It was intended to be a replacement part for the FBI training center, but too many were bought, so it was sold as an action only.  These actions are based on the pre-1964 Winchester actions with the giant claw extractor.  I bought the A1 stock from the training center as a used take-off (more about the stock later).  I ordered a custom Super Match Stainless barrel from Pac Nor in a #8 contour ending in a 0.900 tip.  It is not a lightweight barrel, it was bent to be a bench rest rifle.  I have fired exactly 60 rounds through it during the barrel break in process.  I fired 5 shots, cleaning with bore cleaner, cleaner, lube, then dry after each shot.  It was then extended to 5 sets of 5 shots, cleaning after every 5 shots, then 3 shots of 10 rounds, cleaning after each round.  While doing this, I zero'd and shot groups.  After getting dialed in, I shot a best of 0.38" with all groups (except 1 because I a messed up) were under 0.50". The barrel still needs more rounds to break it in, another 140 rounds or so should get it shooting optimal groups, cleaning after about 30 rounds.  Once past the 200 round point, it should be perfect.  The trigger adjustment was glued, and set at about 6 lbs pull.  I cleansed the glue off and lowered it to about 2 lbs (since it is a bench rifle).

The stock was a used takeoff, but it is a true McMillian stock.  I talked to McMillian about it, and it is covered under the lifetime warranty.  There is a very small nick in the stock near the 4 round magazine.  Because of this, it can be sent to McMillian for repair/refurbishment, or a new stock.  The stock will be returned as new.  I just didn't do it because I ordered a Manners CF gap camo stock for it.  That stock will be done in October, and t is yours, if you want it.  I was waiting to have the rifle Cerakoted after the stock gets here to kind of color match the action, barrel, bolt, and scope.

This will be one of the finest and most accurate rifles you will see outside of a $5000+ rifle!  I would not hesitate to put it against anything available.  600-1000 yards should be simple.  I really don't want to sell it, but I need the money due to the recent issues of the lightning strike.  Insurance just doesn't cover everything!

What you get:
FN SPR rifle with a McMillian stock.  
Vector 6-25x56 illuminated MOA scope w/ sunshade
Cheap soft case to put it in.

title: For Sale/Trade:  CZ-70 .32ACP mfd in 1971 NIB!
postcontent:
CZ-70 caliber 7.65 (.32 ACP), semi-automatic pistol, two 8-round magazines, serial # D98529, all parts matching.
CZ-70 was mfd from 1970 to 1983 at the arms factory at Uherský Brod with the proof stamp of a lion superimposed on an "N" on the left rear of the slide and frame, along with the Czech armory symbol on the left slide and right grip. The last two digits of the year of manufacture are stamped next to the “lion/N”proof stamp. The CZ-70 was replaced by the 9mm Makarov in 1983 and the CZ-70s were imported to the U.S. as surplus firearms. Most of these imported CZ-70s are well-used and fairly worn and have one magazine. This is an early unissued, unfired (except for the test-proof target which is included) CZ-70, dated 1971, in scarce pristine condition, in original box with extra magazine, cleaning brush, original test-proof target which is dated and serial-numbered to the gun.
Note: What might look like blemishes on the finish in the photos is original packing grease, the gun and finish are perfect. $400 local sale or trade.
